				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sun Sep 19, 2004 11:12 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 20409<br /><b>Location:</b> NE Indiana, USA (NTSC)
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Okk wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So let me make sure I have this straight. The nametable can be modified offscreen along one axis. If the camera is scrolling along the other axis, those tiles can't be updated until they are already onscreen. When mirroring is changed, half of the nametable (top or bottom, left or right) is copied to the other half, regardless of where the camera is pointed at the time. Is that about right?</div><br />Nothing is &quot;copied&quot; when <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Mirroring" class="postlink">mirroring</a> is changed. The existing data in the nametables is rearranged. For example, if I put a big A in one nametable and a big B in the other, I'll get this pattern (which in theory repeats indefinitely) in vertical mirroring:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">A B A B<br />A B A B<br />A B A B<br />A B A B<br /></div><br />But if I tell the mapper to switch to horizontal mirroring, the pattern instantly changes:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">A A A A<br />B B B B<br />A A A A<br />B B B B<br /></div><br /><em>Rad Racer</em> relies on making this instant change halfway down the screen at the boundary between sky (whose scrolling wraps horizontally, for which it uses horizontal mirroring) and road (whose scrolling doesn't wrap horizontally, for which it uses vertical mirroring). But for a normal scrolling game, seamless mirroring changes work only when the scrolling is screen-aligned. For example, if the screen is centered over the first letter on the first row or the second letter on the second row, changing the mirroring won't change the display.<br /><br />Adding one gate to the cart PCB produces a mirroring mode that allows screen-aligned direction changes without any mapper writes, as the game can just tell the PPU to switch from one B to another.<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">A B A B<br />B B B B<br />A B A B<br />B B B B<br /></div><br />An OR gate provides L-shaped mirroring. At least one Famicom game is known to use L-shaped mirroring.<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">A B A B<br />B A B A<br />A B A B<br />B A B A<br /></div><br />An XOR gate provides diagonal mirroring.<br /><br />A lot of this might be easier if you provide screenshots.</div>

